SIMPLE: utas
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Utas
<hw>U"tas</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>huitieves</ets>, <ets>witieves</ets>, <ets>witaves</ets>,
<ets>oitieves</ets>, pl. of <ets>huitieve</ets>, <ets>witieve</ets>,
etc., eighth, L. <ets>octavus</ets>. See <er>Octave</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>utis</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(O. Eng. Law)</fld> <def>The eighth day after any
term or feast; the octave; <as>as, the <ex>utas</ex> of St.
Michael.</as></def> <rj><au>Cowell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The marriage was celebrated and Canterbury, and in the
<qex>utas</qex> of St. Hilary next ensuing she was crowned.</q>
<rj><qau>Holinshed.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, festivity; merriment.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Utensil</ent>⟦br⟧
